  "prompt": "Startup Law: How common is the anti-dilution provision for VCs in a Series A round?",
  "response": "Anti-dilution provisions are quite common in Series A funding rounds, particularly in venture capital (VC) term sheets. These provisions are designed to protect investors from equity dilution in the event that the company issues shares at a lower valuation in a subsequent financing round (known as a \"down round\").\n\n### Types of Anti-Dilution Provisions:\n1. **Full Ratchet**: This is the most investor-friendly provision. It adjusts the investor's share price to match the price of the new shares issued in a down round, effectively neutralizing the dilution.\n2. **Weighted Average**: This is a more balanced approach. It adjusts the investor's share price based on a formula that takes into account both the lower price and the number of shares issued in the down round. The weighted average method can be further classified into broad-based and narrow-based, depending on the scope of shares included in the calculation.\n\n### Prevalence in Series A:\nIn Series A rounds, anti-dilution provisions are a standard feature, but the type of provision (full ratchet vs. weighted average) can vary based on the negotiation leverage of the parties involved. Weighted average provisions are more common because they are seen as fairer to both investors and founders, whereas full ratchet provisions are relatively rare and are typically negotiated by very powerful investors.\n\n### Why Anti-Dilution Provisions Matter:\nFor VCs, anti-dilution provisions are a key protection mechanism, especially in the early stages of a startup when there is a higher risk of down rounds. For founders, these provisions can be a double-edged sword: while they make the investment more attractive, they can also significantly dilute the founders' equity in a down round.\n\nIn summary, anti-dilution provisions are a standard part of Series A term sheets, with weighted average provisions being the most common. The specifics of the provision are subject to negotiation and can vary based on the relative bargaining power of the investors and the founders.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
